stop_info: The station is named after Victor Hugo (1802-1885), a poet, writer, member of the French national assembly and later senator.
The station was named after the Battle of Alma - a Franco-British victory against the Russians in the Crimean War in 1854.
For the Exposition Internationale of 1937, the old Palais du Trocadéro was partially demolished and rebuilt as the Palais de Chaillot which now tops the hill.

The station was named for the Elysian Fields - 'heaven' in Greek mythology. The boulevard was laid out in the 17th century and is part of the axe historique, linking place de la Concorde with the Arc de Triomphe.
The station is home to the famous Moulin Rouge, which was co-founded in 1889 by businessmen Charles Zidler and Joseph Oller.
Place de la Concorde was designed by Ange-Jacques Gabriel in 1755 as a moat-skirted octagon between the Champs-Elysées to the west and the Tuileries Garden to the east.
Filled with fountains, classical sculptures and magnificent panoramas every way you turn, the Tuileries Gardens was laid out in 1664 by André Le Nôtre, architect of the gardens at Versailles.
Konwn initially as the Palais-Cardinal, a personal residence of Cardinal Richelieu. After Richelieu's death in 1642 the palace became the property of the King gaining the new name.
Designed in 1860 by Charles Garnier - then an unknown 35-year-old architect - the opera house was part of Baron Haussmann's massive urban renovation project.

The station is home to Élysée Montmartre, a ballroom inaugurated in 1807. It was made famous by the quadrille naturaliste - later to become the French Cancan - a frenetic dance in which the women throw up their skirts in time to the music.
In this station, the French resistance launched its first attack against the Nazi occupier during World War II.
In 1808, Napoleon I laid the foundation of the Palais Brongniart, designed by the architect Alexandre-Théodore Brongniart and intended to host the Paris Stock Exchange.
Gare de l’Est, built between 1847 and 1850, is the departure point for trains to eastern France. During WWI, thousands of men left for the front from this mainline station.
The station will later be renamed after Jacques Bonsergent who was the first civilian Parisian shot during the German occupation in 1940.

The station was named after the museum of Arts et métiers. This museum was founded in the 18th century by Abbot Grégoire as 'a store for useful new inventions'. Housed in the former Benedictine church and priory of Saint-Martin-des-Champs, it exhibits some of the world's greatest inventions, from Pascal's calculating devices and celestial spheres to the first computers, steam-powered vehicles, and even airplanes (including the monoplane of Louis Blériot who flew across the English Channel in 1909)

Louis VI created Halles (markets) in 1137 for the merchants who converged on the city centre to sell their wares, and for over 800 years they were, in the words of the French novelist Émile Zola, the 'belly of Paris'.

Napoléon Bonaparte's military campaigns at the turn of the 19th century brought constant influx of holdings to the Louvre museum, as his soldiers carried off treasures from each invaded country. During WWII the most precious artworks were hidden there, while the remainder was looted.
Ever since 1357, the City of Paris' administration has been located on the same location where the Hôtel de Ville stands today.

The station is named after the Grand Châtelet, a castle over the northern approach to the old Pont au Change over the Seine to the Île de la Cité, which was demolished by Napoléon in 1802. Châtelet is a medieval French term for barbican, a small castle that overlooks a bridge.

Île de la Cité was the site of the first settlement in Paris (c 3rd century BC) and later the centre of Roman Lutetia. The island remained the hub of royal and ecclesiastical power, even after the city spread to both banks of the Seine in the Middle Ages.

The station was the site of a fire and stampede that caused the worst catastrophe in the history of the Paris Metro, killing 84 people on 10 August 1903. Indeed, a technical problem triggered a fire in-between two stations. Passengers were evacuated at the Couronnes station but people remained on the platform, asking for a ticket refund. Suddenly, light went out and left place to the panic movement of the crowd that led to the disaster.
It is in this station that the first moving staircase will be installed in 1909, which will be covering thirty centimeters a second. Hundreds of other escalators will follow that first installation.
This station will be absorbed into Gambetta station following a line reorganisation in 1969. It is now a ghost station.
Born in 1838, Léon Gambetta helped create the Third Republic. Maybe this is why the lawyer and statesman’s name graces the former terminus of Line 3.
The station will be later renamed from Bagnolet to Alexandre Dumas, a French writer.

Before it became a prison, the Bastille St-Antoine was a defensive fortress with eight immense towers and a wide moat. It was built by Charles V in the late 14th century and transformed into a prison during the reign of Louis XIII (1610–43). Famous occupants included Voltaire, the Marquis de Sade, and the Man in the Iron Mask.

The station closed on 2 September 1939, as a result of the mobilization of employees of the Compagnie du chemin de fer métropolitain de Paris (CMP) in WWII. It was never reopened and today serves as a training centre for RATP agents.

The train station originally opened to the public in 1849 under the name 'Embarcadère de chemin de fer de Paris à Montereau'. It was then refurbished for the World Exposition of 1900. On multiple levels, it is considered a classic example of the architecture of its time. Most notable is the large clock tower atop one corner of the station, similar in style to the clock tower of t

Widely known for having the most active guillotines during the French Revolution, the square was renamed Place de la Nation on Bastille Day, 14 July 1880, under the Third Republic. The square includes a large bronze sculpture, the Triomphe de la République

Just before the Revolution, Paris' cemeteries were bursting at the seams, spreading disease. To solve the problem, millions of bones were transferred underground into tunnels of the Paris Catacombs that sprawl beneath the Denfert-Rochereau district.
The station is named after the scientist René-Antoine Ferchault de Réaumur, and for the port of Sevastopol in Crimea, the scene of the Siege of Sevastopol (1854–1855) during the Crimean War.

Widely known for having the most active guillotines during the French Revolution, the square was renamed Place de la Nation on Bastille Day, 14 July 1880, under the Third Republic.The square includes a large bronze sculpture, the Triomphe de la République

Widely known for having the most active guillotines during the French Revolution, the square was renamed Place de la Nation on Bastille Day, 14 July 1880, under the Third Republic.The square includes a large bronze sculpture, the Triomphe de la République.

Arc de Triomphe stands sentinel in the center of the Étoile (star) roundabout. The arch was first commissioned in 1806 in the style of a Roman triumphal arch, following Napoléon's victory at Austerlitz the year before.
The station will be later renamed and become Eglise d'Auteuil.
The grassy Champ de Mars – running southeast from the Eiffel Tower – was originally used as a parade ground for the cadets of the 18th-century École Militaire.
The military school counts Napoléon Bonaparte among its graduates

The Hôtel des Invalides was built in the 1670s by Louis XIV to house 4000 invalides (disabled war veterans). On 14 July 1789, a mob broke into the building and seized 32,000 rifles before heading on to the prison at Bastille and the start of the French Revolution.

Place de la Concorde was first laid out in 1755 and originally named after King Louis XV, but its royal associations meant that it took centre stage during the Revolution – Louis XVI was the first to be guillotined here in 1793.

Église de la Madeleine, a neoclassical church, designed by Barthélémy Vignon in 1806 as a 'temple of glory' for Napoleon Bonaparte. The exterior, which mirrors the Assemblée Nationale on the other side of Place de la Concorde, is marked by fluted Corinthian columns, while interior highlights include a wonderful frieze of the Last Judgment and a painting of the history of Christianity by Jules-Claude Ziegler.
The station is renamed after 1945 to Corentin Cariou, who was shot by the Nazis as a hostage during WWII.
During WWI, Parisians often took sanctuary in the Métro stations to escape bombardments. On March 11 1918, a German bombing raid causes a panic in the Bolivar station, killing 71 persons.
Station renamed from Vaugirard to Saint-Placide in honor of saint Placide, a disciple of saint Benoît.
In this station, the French resistance launched its first attack against the Nazi occupier during World War II.
This is the only station in Paris named after a woman until 2007, when Pierre Curie station renamed to Pierre et Marie Curie.

The station name changed from Caumartin to Havre-Caumartin in-between 1915 and 1950. This station is home to Printemps. Spread across three buildings, the upscale department store has been luring shoppers since 1865.

Hôtel Drouot is Paris' over a century old auction house. With everything from old clothes to haute couture gowns and from tchotchkes to ornate Chinese lacquered boxes, rare books, and wine, Drouot sells it all.
The station renamed to Grands Boulevards to avoid confusion suggesting that the station was in the Montmartre district.

Station closed in 1938 due to close proximity to station Strasbourg-Saint-Denis. In 1999, the RATP will refurbish the station's eastern entrance area into a homeless shelter run by the Salvation Army.

Station closed in 1938 due to close proximity to station Strasbourg-Saint-Denis. In 1999, the RATP will refurbish the station's eastern entrance area into a homeless shelter run by the Salvation Army.
With 36 meters underground, this station is the deepest metro station in Paris
Station is now renamed to Assemblée Nationale to reflect the updated name of the Chamber of Deputies.
The station closed during WWII and never reopened due to its proximity to the station Sèvres – Babylone.

Initially the residential quarters of the Cluny Abbots, the Hôtel de Cluny was later occupied by Alexandre du Sommerard, who moved here in 1833 with his collection of medieval and Renaissance objects. Bought by the state after his death, the museum opened a decade later, retaining the Hôtel de Cluny's original layout and features. Today it holds some fascinating relics, not least of which is an entire room (No 8) dedicated to statuary from Notre Dame's façade, removed during the Revolution and later used to support the foundations of a private mansion.
The name Censier derived from the original name Rue Sans Chef, which means 'cul-de-sac' (dead-end).
The station is renamed from Marcadet - Balagny to Guy Môquet who was a member of the French Resistance and killed at the age of seventeen.
The station was called Berlin before the outbreak of WWI

The station was renamed from Montparnasse to Montparnasse-Bienvenüe in-between 1915 and 1950. Fulgence Bienvenüe (1852-1936) is an engineer who studied at the prestigious Ecole polytechnique and Ponts et Chaussées engineering schools. His major achievement, however, is the Paris metro, which he designed in 1896.

Stations Aubervilliers and La Villette were merged into one station called Aubervilliers - Boulevard de la Villette. After WWII, the station is renamed to Stalingrad in honor of the Soviet victory at the Battle of Stalingrad.
